sections.History:
[[File:Night's_Watch_vows.jpg|thumb|Night's Watch recruits taking their vows before a weirwood.]]
During the [[Andal Invasion]] six thousand years ago, the Andals cut down most of the weirwood trees in southern Westeros, to suppress worship of the Old Gods in favor of the Andal's new religion, the [[Faith of the Seven]]. The only weirwoods still in the south are the handful of heart trees that survived in castle godswoods that were converted to secular gardens, instead of being destroyed. Weirwoods also survive in southern Westeros on the [[Isle of Faces]] in [[Gods Eye]] lake, in the southern [[The Riverlands|Riverlands]]. Weirwoods only still grow in significant numbers in the forests of the North. [[Beyond the Wall]], they are even more prevalent.&lt;ref&gt;[[Complete Guide to Westeros]]: &quot;The Old Gods and the New&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;

[[File:BranWeirwood.jpg|thumb|[[Bran Stark]] before a weirwood with a carved face.]]
The area around the Weirwood where [[Bran Stark]] meets the [[Three-eyed raven]] is shown to destroy wights. It is stated by a [[Leaf|child of the forest]] that they &quot;hold no power here&quot;, though it is unclear whether it is because of the tree, the reason why the tree is there, or some other factor.&lt;ref&gt;&quot;[[The Children]]&quot;&lt;/ref&gt;
